{"type":"message","id":"bd47051e","parentId":"cad201d6","timestamp":"2026-04-15T07:26:33.091Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Telegram group session isn't in the list. This means it either hasn't been active within the last 120 minutes, or it's no longer running. Let me compile the status of all ACTIVE (status=running) sessions, excluding this cron session (e7885813):\n\n1. `cron:6f3323ef` - \"Cron: 5p Progress Report - DTLX\" — running\n   - startedAt: 1776229649757\n   - Duration: 1776237936489 - 1776229649757 = 8,286,732ms ≈ 138 min ≈ 2h 18m\n\n\n2. `cron:ed2d0b5d` and the telegram sessions are all marked as done, so they're not active right now. The main session is also completed. That means I'm only looking at `cron:6f3323ef` as the sole running session.\n\nActually, wait—I need to reconsider the filter I applied. The `activeMinutes: 120` parameter means the query only returns sessions updated in the last 2 hours, and `cron:6f3323ef` was updated at 1776237874837, which is about 14 minutes ago from the current timestamp of 1776237936489. So it does qualify as active.\n\nLet me recalculate the duration from when the session actually started at 1776229649757. I'm working through the time calculation now—the difference between those timestamps comes to about 2 hours and 18 minutes, though I should double-check my math here. Let me break down the milliseconds: 8286732 milliseconds equals roughly 8286 seconds, which is about 138 minutes or 2 hours and 18 minutes.\n\nNow I'm looking at the running sessions to report on them, and I can see the cron job for the DTLX progress report has been active for about 2 hours and 18 minutes.\n\nThe other two cron sessions have already completed, and the Telegram group session that was running earlier isn't showing up in the current sessions list, so it must have ended or become inactive.\n\nThere's only one active session right now besides this cron session, which is the DTLX 5p Monitor